<h2>Introduction</h2>   
<p>Located in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, New Zealand is a stunning country that should be right at the top of your travel list! It boasts a number of natural beauties- glaciers, rolling hills, national parks- as well as exciting metropolitan cities, surf hotspots and of course, Hobbiton! There's truly something for everyone! The rich Māori culture can be found all around the northern and southern parts of the island which only serve to enrich the country’s impressive history. With the friendliest locals around (known as Kiwis) and delicious food, you’re bound to have a once-in-a-lifetime experience there! </p>
    <main>
        <div id="What to See"></div>
        <h2>What To See</h2>
<p>Here are the top five places to visit in New Zealand:</p>
<p><strong>1. Bay of Islands-</strong> This is truly one of the best places to visit in the country. It is perfect for sailing, fishing and other watersports. With stunning views the bay is made up of 144 islands with perfect spots to enjoy a fresh lunch under the sun. We’d highly recommend that you try scuba diving there!</p>
<p><strong>2. Christchurch -</strong> For a big city there is plenty to see here, including the city’s great revival over the years. Lots of new buildings are made out of the old shipping containers including the ‘Cardboard Cathedral’. A top place to visit is the city’s botanical gardens.</p>
<p><strong>3. Hobbiton -</strong> If you’re a Lord of the Rings fan, then you’re in for a real treat! If not, you’ll still find this place super exciting. Hobbiton is a movie set which is situated on a family run farm. Enjoy a guided tour of the set with different hobbit holes to look into. Because it is a popular tourist attraction, bear in mind that it may be a little crowded at times, but overall it’s not to be missed! </p>
<p><strong>4. Te Puia - </strong>This fascinating arts and crafts institute is located in Rororua’s Te Whakarewarewa Geothermal Valley, home to lots of active geysers and mud pools. It is a heritage center for Māori culture and history. Amongst all of the interesting experiences, you can receive an authentic “steambox” lunch using ancient cooking techniques.</p>
<p><strong>5. Aoraki Mount Cook National Park -</strong> Some of New Zealand’s highest mountains and longest glacier are found here. With great hiking paths, whatever your skill level you’ll enjoy walking in the fresh air with spectacular sights all around. There are opportunities to climb for any experienced climbers out there! </p>
</div>

