<div id="Transport">    
<h2>Transport</h2>
<p>You’ll be relieved to know that it is super easy to get around New Zealand. Public transport is prominent in all cities and most towns. Buses operate quite regularly and both Auckland and Wellington have city-suburban rail services. </p>
<p>Public Transport: All New Zealand cities and most towns have buses, and Auckland and Wellington both have city-suburban rail services. Go to Our regions and cities section for more detail.</p>
<p>Cars: Renting a car is pretty easy, though buying a car will weirdly cost you less money. Most rental companies have depots in town where you can pick up your cars. Remember that everyone drives on the left in New Zealand! Before searching for a good company make sure to check NZTA’s advice on safety and mechanical conditions of cars.</p> 
<p>Taxis: If you don’t want to rent a car or use public transport, there are a number of taxi companies who can get you around places. Uber also operates- just download the Uber app and you’re read to go! </p>
<p>Planes: For longer trips, it is possible to fly. Between Auckland and Wellington a flight will usually take an hour, compared with eight hours of driving. The two main travel airlines are Air New Zealand and Jetstar and a few smaller regional operators. Check the timetables and fares online- usually the price of tickets aren’t too expensive.</p>
</div>

<div>
<div id="Where to stay">    
<h2>Where To Stay</h2>
<p>Depending on where you go in New Zealand there are plenty of great places to stay which are safe and full of friendly travelers and New Zealanders. The costs of rooms depends on the type of hostel or hostel and what extra features you would like, including how much privacy you’re hoping for.</p> 
<p><strong>For a full breakdown of the different places to stay according to various cities and prices, <a href="https://www.thehotelguru.com/best-hotels-in/new-zealand" target=_blank">click here.</strong></a></p> 
</div>

<div>
<div id="Language tips">    
<h2>Language Tips</h2>
<p>New Zealand has three official languages: English, Maori and New Zealand Sign Language. Maori is particularly interesting for it belongs to the indigenous Maāori people and it was made an official language by statue in 1987. The language can be used in official settings, like court. It is closely related to Tahitian and Cook Islands Māori. Since the 1970s, it has been revitalised in the New Zealand community and the number of speakers has grown considerably. </p>
<p>Fear not, you won’t be expected to speak all three official languages fluently. English can be used all around the island with absolute ease, since 91.6% of the population speak it and it has been the predominant language for a while. In terms of English pronunciation, New Zealanders are very close to their neighbours, the Australians! </p>
<p>Much like any English speakers, there comes a bit of local linho which will be handy to know on your holidays! A few examples are:</p>
<li>All good: That’s ok, never mind</li>
<li>Sweet as: Great, good, fine</li>
<li>Choice as: That’s great, awesome, sure</li>
<p><strong>For a full list of common Kiwi Lingo, <a href="https://www.discovernewzealand.com/blog-new-zealand-slang-305" target="_blank">click here.</strong></a></p>
</div>

<div>
<div id="Safety">    
<h2>Safety</h2>
<p>By international standards, New Zealand is one of the safest countries in the world, especially for female solo travellers. In the 2017 international Global Peace Index, it was rated the world’s second safest country after Iceland, out of 126 countries. </p>
<p>However, as with any country it’s really important to stay safe and to not take any risks. Petty theft can be common in the country; wherever you go make sure to keep an eye on your possessions and look out for anyone who is acting suspiciously. Do not leave any valuables in cars as thieves tend to target vehicles. </p>
<p>In terms of natural disasters, earthquakes pose a substantial risk with large quakes happening at any time. Familiarise yourself with best practice during earthquakes. The same can be said for tsunamis; if one were to occur you should move to high ground immediately. Likewise, volcano eruptions are common; the last eruption took place on White Island in the Bay of Plenty on 9 December 2019- follow the advice of local authorities and notify official bodies (Department of Conservation) of your whereabouts if you’re rock climbing or hiking in a remote area. </p>
</div>
